title="Proof by contradiction">Proof by contradiction</fr:link>. Assume for contradiction that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> converges to two distinct points <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y\in  X]]></fr:tex>. Then by <fr:link
type="local"
href="gt-000Y.xml"
addr="gt-000Y"
title="Hausdorff space">Hausdorff property</fr:link>, there are disjoint open neighborhoods <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{x}\ni  x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{y}\ni  y]]></fr:tex>. By definition of <fr:link
type="local"
href="gt-000O.xml"
addr="gt-000O"
title="Convergence of sequence in a topological space">Convergence of sequence in a topological space</fr:link>, there are two positive integers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[N_{x}\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[N_{y}\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> such that for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq  N_{x}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\in  U_{x}]]></fr:tex> and for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq  N_{y}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\in  U_{y}]]></fr:tex>. Setting <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[N=\max (N_{x},N_{y})]]></fr:tex>, then for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq  N]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\in  U_{x}\cap  U_{y}]]></fr:tex> which is disjoint. Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> cannot converge to more than one point in a Hausdorff space.</fr:p><html:span
